**Sec. 20001**
This section appropriates $10.4 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to improve military personnel quality of life, including $2.9 billion for housing allowances and $2 billion for the Defense Health Program. Specific allocations include $1 billion for military unaccompanied housing modernization, $100 million for tuition and child care fee assistance, and $50 million for special pays and bonuses. The bill also authorizes a temporary increase in the value of privatized military housing projects from 33.33% to 60% and extends the authority for private sector housing contracts until September 30, 2029. Additionally, $100 million is designated for the Defense Community Infrastructure Program and $62 million for childcare center staffing modernization.

**Sec. 20002**
The Secretary of Defense receives $18.5 billion in appropriations for fiscal year 2025 to expand the naval shipbuilding industrial base and procure new vessels. Major funding includes $4.6 billion for a second Virginia-class submarine, $5.4 billion for two additional Guided Missile Destroyers, and $2.7 billion for T-AO oilers. Significant investments target industrial capacity, such as $750 million for supplier development, $500 million for advanced manufacturing techniques, and $450 million for additive manufacturing wire production. The section also funds the procurement of Landing Ships Medium, unmanned surface and underwater vehicles, and the lease of ships for Marine Corps operations.

**Sec. 20003**
This section appropriates $20.2 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to enhance integrated air and missile defense technologies and homeland defense layers. Key allocations include $7.2 billion for military space-based sensors, $5.6 billion for space-based boost phase intercept capabilities, and $2.2 billion for accelerating hypersonic defense systems. Funding also supports $1.975 billion for improved ground-based missile defense radars and $408 million for restoring test range infrastructure in the Indo-Pacific Command area. The bill further provides $530 million for the design and construction of a Missile Defense Agency instrumentation range safety ship.

**Sec. 20004**
The Secretary of Defense is appropriated $23.5 billion for fiscal year 2025 to expand munitions production and strengthen the defense supply chain, including $1 billion for next-generation automated munitions factories. Specific funding targets long-range missiles, with $400 million for anti-ship missiles and $300 million for medium-range ballistic missiles, alongside $1 billion for the National Defense Stockpile Transaction Fund to secure critical minerals. The section establishes a $5 billion investment pool for critical minerals supply chains and a $500 million credit program account to subsidize up to $100 billion in loans for related industries. Additional funds support the development of counter-unmanned aerial systems, hypersonic strike programs, and the expansion of solid rocket motor industrial bases.

**Sec. 20005**
This section appropriates $13.5 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to scale low-cost weapons and innovative technologies into production. Major allocations include $2 billion for the Defense Innovation Unit to scale commercial technology, $1.5 billion for low-cost cruise missiles, and $1.4 billion to expand the small unmanned aerial system industrial base. The bill also funds $1 billion for accelerating the procurement of innovative technologies, $600 million for Strategic Capabilities Office programs, and $500 million for advanced 5G/6G military technologies. Furthermore, $1.685 billion is designated for military cryptographic modernization and $250 million for the expansion of the artificial intelligence ecosystem.

**Sec. 20006**
The Secretary of Defense receives $380 million in appropriations for fiscal year 2025 to improve departmental efficiency and cybersecurity. The largest portion, $200 million, is allocated to deploy automation and artificial intelligence to accelerate financial statement audits under title 10, United States Code. Additional funding includes $150 million for business systems replacement to support these audits and $20 million for Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency cybersecurity programs. The section also provides $10 million to improve the budgetary and programmatic infrastructure of the Office of the Secretary of Defense.

**Sec. 20007**
This section appropriates $12.5 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to enhance air superiority capabilities across the military services. Significant funding includes $3.15 billion to increase F-15EX aircraft production, $750 million to accelerate the FA/XX aircraft program, and $400 million for F-47 aircraft production. The bill also allocates $678 million for the Collaborative Combat Aircraft program, $474 million for EA-37B production, and $440 million to increase C-130J production. Additional funds support preventing the retirement of F-22 and F-15E aircraft, accelerating V-22 improvements, and developing long-range strike aircraft for the Air Force and Navy.

**Sec. 20008**
The Secretary of Defense and the Administrator of the National Nuclear Security Administration (NNSA) receive $20.5 billion in appropriations for fiscal year 2025 to modernize nuclear forces. DOD allocations include $4.5 billion for B-21 bomber production expansion, $2.5 billion for Sentinel ICBM risk reduction, and $2 billion for the nuclear-armed sea-launched cruise missile. NNSA funding covers $1 billion for facility construction, $750 million each for primary and secondary capability modernization, and $400 million for the sea-launched cruise missile warhead. The section also provides $148 million for D5 missile motor production and $120 million for domestic uranium enrichment centrifuge deployment.

**Sec. 20009**
This section appropriates $13.5 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to improve capabilities within the United States Indo-Pacific Command. Major investments include $3.65 billion for military satellites and their protection, $1 billion for offensive cyber operations, and $1.1 billion for infrastructure development in the region. Funding also supports $450 million for airfield development, $365 million for Army exercises in the Western Pacific, and $200 million for the Guam Defense System program. Additional allocations cover mission networks, anti-submarine sonar arrays, and the X-37B military spacecraft program.

**Sec. 20010**
The Secretary of Defense receives $18.5 billion in appropriations for fiscal year 2025 to improve the readiness of the Department of Defense. Significant funding includes $2.5 billion for Air Force facilities sustainment, $2 billion for Navy depot and shipyard modernization, and $1.5 billion for Army depot modernization. The bill also allocates $2.118 billion for Air Force aircraft spares and repairs, $1.64 billion for Special Operations Command equipment, and $500 million for National Guard unit readiness. Additional funds support the procurement of Army wheeled combat vehicles, Marine Corps amphibious vehicles, and next-generation vertical lift aircraft.

**Sec. 20011**
This section appropriates $1 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to support border operations and counter-drug missions. The funds are designated for the deployment of military personnel, operations and maintenance activities, and the construction of national defense areas in accordance with title 10, United States Code. Specifically, the money covers the temporary detention of migrants on Department of Defense installations and support for counter-transnational criminal organization missions. The appropriation remains available until September 30, 2029.

**Sec. 20012**
The Inspector General of the Department of Defense receives $10 million in appropriations for fiscal year 2025 to monitor activities funded under this title. The oversight is specifically focused on programs with mutual technological dependencies, related data management considerations, and those vulnerable to supply chain disruptions. These funds remain available until September 30, 2029, to ensure accountability for the massive investments outlined in the preceding sections.

**Sec. 20013**
This section authorizes the appropriation of funds for military construction, land acquisition, and military family housing functions for each military department. It mandates that the Secretary of each military department submit a detailed spending plan by project to the Senate and House Armed Services Committees within 30 days of enactment. The authorization covers all funds made available by this title for military construction projects, ensuring transparency and oversight of physical infrastructure investments. No specific dollar amounts are listed in this section, as they are authorized for appropriation based on the needs of the military departments. [end of text]


